sec.p:
The load received at birth (k0), along with the amount accumulated in its lifetime (λT0), is the damage a bacterium will segregate to its daughters according to the asymmetry coefficient (a), ranging from 0 (complete asymmetry) to 0.5 (symmetry):




k1=(k0+λT0)a;







k2=(k0+λT0)(1-a).

This asymmetric inheritance will affect the doubling times of the offspring, causing old daughters, which receive the higher load (k2), to slow down compared with their young siblings. The doubling times of each daughter, T1 and T2, are given by




T1=(1-k1)-(1-k1)2-2Πλλ;







T2=(1-k2)-(1-k2)2-2Πλλ.

Estimates of doubling time equilibrium were determined as the points where prediction lines cross the identity, which can be calculated as




α=a1-a;







T^1=1-1-4Πλ(12+α)2λ(12+α);







T^2=1-1-4Πλ(12+1α)2λ(12+1α).
